list.name: Changes
list.comment: Finished the `encode` method by using the two previously coded methods

task.summary: Created the compressors package where different compression algorithms will be implemented, and added the base interface all implementations will adhere to

Created the `lzw` package - an inner package that will contain the logic of the LZW compression algorithm. The init file holds the main Compressor, and its skeleton was written. A class representing the dictionary used in the encoding process was also written comprehensively

Two changes: 1) A new private attribute 'keys_set' was created. This change heavily optimizes searching for a key, from O(n) time complexity (key in self.__encoded_values.keys()) to O(1) time complexity (key in self.__keys_set)
2) The 'current_size' property and attribute was removed. Instead, the __len__ method is implemented to return the amount of keys in the dictionary (which is also the amount of entries)

Big change: The purpose of the encoding dictionary is to assign indices to given keys and make sure each index is unique. For this reason, it does not make sense to allow outside code to change the index of an existing key using __setitem__. For this reason, inserting keys is now done using the 'insert' method, and a new attribute keeps track of the next index that will be mapped upon insertion

Created the function that parses input data into a list of encoder dictionary indices. Note that this method does not handle the potential `TooManyEncodingsException`. This is intentional, and the exception will be later propagated upwards in the `encode` method

Created the function that takes the parsed indices, and turns them into one `bytes` object. The function needs to pad those indices for the decompression step to know where an index starts and ends, but it does so while using as little memory as needed
Finished the `encode` method by using the two previously coded methods
